"Leuliette E.W., Willis J.K.","Balancing the sea level budget",2011,"Oceanography","24","2",,"122","129",,,10.5670/oceanog.2011.32,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959289725&partnerID=40&md5=4d4427399b0c46bf343407d98a6ec28e","Research Oceanographer, Laboratory for Satellite Altimetry, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Silver Spring, MD, United States; Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA, United States","Leuliette, E.W., Research Oceanographer, Laboratory for Satellite Altimetry, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Silver Spring, MD, United States; Willis, J.K., Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA, United States","Sea level rise is both a powerful impact of and indicator for global warming and climate change. Observing sea level change, as well as its causes, is therefore a top priority for scientists and society at large. By measuring the ocean's temperature, salinity, mass, and surface height, the relative sources of recent sea level rise can be discerned. With these observations, sea level change is determined in terms of total sea level and its two major components, ocean mass and steric (density-related) sea level. The sea level budget is closed when the sum of the independent components agrees with measurements of total sea level, indicating that the observations can be used to interpret the causes of sea level change. While nearly global monitoring of sea level from space-based radar altimeters has been available since the early 1990s, satellite gravity missions capable of weighing changes in ocean mass have been available for less than 10 years. Even more recently, the Argo array of profiling floats achieved a level of coverage that now allows assessment of global sea level change due to temperature and salinity in the upper 2,000 m of the ocean. Only during the overlapping period of all three observing systems can the sea level budget be directly addressed by observations. © 2011 by The Oceanography Society. All rights reserved.",,,,,,,,"Beckley, B., Zelensky, N., Holmes, S., Lemoine, F., Ray, R., Mitchum, G., Desai, S., Brown, S., Assessment of the Jason-2 extension to the TOPEX/Poseidon, Jason-1 sea-surface height time series for global mean sea level monitoring (2010) Marine Geodesy, 33 (1), pp. 447-471. , doi:10.1080/01490419.2010.491029; Bindoff, N., Willebrand, J., Artale, V., Cazenave, A., Gregory, J., Gulev, S., Hanawa, K., Nojiri, Y., (2007) Observations: Oceanic Climate Change and Sea Level, pp. 385-432. , in Climate Change 2007: The Physical Science Basis. Contribution of Working Group I to the Fourth Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, S. Solomon, D. Qin, M. Manning, Z. Chen, M. Marquis, K.B. Averyt, M. Tignor, and H.L. Miller, eds, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, United Kingdom and New York, NY, USA; Cazenave, A., Llovel, W., Contemporary sea level rise (2010) Annual Review of Marine Science, 2 (1), pp. 145-173. , doi:10.1007/s10236-010-0324-0; Cazenave, A., Dominh, K., Guinehut, S., Berthier, E., Llovel, W., Ramillien, G., Ablain, M., Larnicol, G., Sea level budget over 2003-2008: A reevaluation from GRACE space gravimetry, satellite altimetry and Argo (2009) Global and Planetary Change, 65 (1-2), pp. 83-88. , doi:10.1016/j.gloplacha.2008.10.004; Chambers, D., Observing seasonal steric sea level variations with GRACE and satellite altimetry (2006) Journal of Geophysical Research, 111 (3), pp. C03010. , doi:10.1029/2005JC002914; Chambers, D.P., Willis, J.K., Low-frequency exchange of mass between ocean basins (2009) Journal of Geophysical Research, 114 (C11), pp. C11008. , doi:10.1029/2009JC005518; Chambers, D.P., Willis, J.K., A global evaluation of ocean bottom pressure from GRACE, OMCT, and steric-corrected altimetry (2010) Journal of Atmospheric and Oceanic Technology, 27 (8), pp. 1395-1402. , doi:10.1175/2010JTECHO738.1; Chambers, D.P.,